    "reasoning": "First, identify the prime pair (p, q') where q' divides p² + 4 and p divides q'² + 4. Testing small primes, the valid ordered pair (29, 5) satisfies 5 | 29² + 4 (845/5 = 169) and 29 | 5² + 4 (29/29 = 1). Here, (p² + 4)/q' = 845/5 = 169 = 13², so q = 13 (prime). Thus, k = q - 11 = 13 - 11 = 2.\n\nNext, solve for the minimum of a² + b² + c² given abc + a + b + c = ab + bc + ca + 5. Rewrite the equation as (a-1)(b-1)(c-1) = 4. Substitute x = a-1, y = b-1, z = c-1, so xyz = 4. Minimize (x+1)² + (y+1)² + (z+1)². Testing symmetric cases, setting x = y = -2 (so a = b = -1) gives z = 1 (c = 2). This satisfies the constraint and yields (-1)² + (-1)² + 2² = 6. Verification via Lagrange multipliers confirms this is the minimum.",
